Gyokurin-in, a temple of the {{ill|Shugendō|ja|修験道|12=draft}} sect (Honzan-ha) founded in {{ill|790 AD|ja|790th year|12=draft}} (the 9th year of {{ill|Enryaku|ja|延暦|12=draft}}), was later forced into closure during the early {{ill|Meiji Period|ja|明治|12=draft}} due to the separation of Shinto and Buddhism.<ref name="神社">{{Cite book|lang=ja|title={{ill|Saitama Shrines: Shrines of Kita-Adachi, Kodama, and Minami Saitama|ja|埼玉の神社 北足立・児玉・南埼玉|12=draft}}|publisher={{ill|Saitama Prefecture Shrine Agency|ja|埼玉県神社庁|12=draft}}|date=1998|pages=142–143}}</ref>

Separated from Gyokurin-in, this shrine was originally known as "Kashima-sha" and was designated as a village shrine under the Modern Shrine Ranking System in {{ill|1873 AD|ja|1873rd year|12=draft}} (Meiji 6). In {{ill|1908 AD|ja|1908th year|12=draft}} (Meiji 41), during a consolidation process, ten surrounding shrines were merged and the shrine was renamed "Nakao Shrine" based on its local place name. (This merger was only administrative; the individual shrines still exist.)<ref>{{R|"神社"}}</ref>

