'''Nakao Shrine''' (中尾神社, なかおじんじゃ) is a Shinto shrine located in {{ill|Saitama Prefecture|ja|埼玉県|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Saitama City|ja|さいたま市|qq=draft}}, Midori Ward ({{ill|Midori Ward|ja|緑区 (さいたま市)|qq=draft}}) of Japan.

== History ==
The founding date of the shrine is unknown. However, it is believed to have existed at least since the late {{ill|Edo Period|ja|江戸時代|qq=draft}}, as it is mentioned in the geographical work 『{{ill|New Edition Musashi Fudoki-kō|ja|新編武蔵風土記稿|qq=draft}}』 as the subsidiary shrine "Kashima Myōjin-sha" of "Gyokurin-in."<ref name="">{{sfn|新編武蔵風土記稿 中尾村 鹿島明神社}}</ref>

Gyokurin-in, a temple of the {{ill|Shugendō|ja|修験道|qq=draft}} sect (Honzan-ha) founded in {{ill|790 AD|ja|790th year|qq=draft}} (the 9th year of {{ill|Enryaku|ja|延暦|qq=draft}}), was later forced into closure during the early {{ill|Meiji Period|ja|明治|1=Meiji era|qq=draft}} due to the separation of Shinto and Buddhism.<ref name="神社">{{Cite book|lang=ja|title={{ill|Saitama Shrines: Shrines of Kita-Adachi, Kodama, and Minami Saitama|ja|埼玉の神社 北足立・児玉・南埼玉}}|publisher={{ill|Saitama Prefecture Shrine Agency|ja|埼玉県神社庁|qq=draft}}|date=1998|pages=142–143}}</ref>

Separated from Gyokurin-in, this shrine was originally known as "Kashima-sha" and was designated as a village shrine under the Modern Shrine Ranking System in {{ill|1873 AD|ja|1873rd year|qq=draft}} (Meiji 6). In {{ill|1908 AD|ja|1908th year|qq=draft}} (Meiji 41), during a consolidation process, ten surrounding shrines were merged and the shrine was renamed "Nakao Shrine" based on its local place name. (This merger was only administrative; the individual shrines still exist.)<ref>{{R|"神社"}}</ref>

== Transportation ==
* A 26‑minute walk from {{ill|Higashi-Urawa Station|ja|東浦和駅|qq=draft}}
* From the {{ill|Kokusai Kōgyō Bus|ja|国際興業バス|qq=draft}} (Higashi-Urawa Station, Saitama East Office, line "Higashi-Urawa 03"), get off at "Nakao Daini Kōen" and walk 4 minutes.

