'''Nakao Shrine''' (中尾神社, なかおじんじゃ) is a Shinto shrine located in {{ill|Saitama Prefecture|ja|埼玉県|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saitama Prefecture|qq=}}, {{ill|Saitama City|ja|さいたま市|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saitama City|qq=}}, Midori Ward ({{ill|Midori Ward|ja|緑区 (さいたま市)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Midori Ward|qq=}}) of Japan.

== History ==
The founding date of the shrine is unknown. However, it is believed to have existed at least since the late {{ill|Edo Period|ja|江戸時代|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Edo Period|qq=}}, as it is mentioned in the geographical work 『{{ill|New Edition Musashi Fudoki-kō|ja|新編武蔵風土記稿|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/New Edition Musashi Fudoki-kō|qq=}}』 as the subsidiary shrine "Kashima Myōjin-sha" of "Gyokurin-in."<ref name="">{{sfn|新編武蔵風土記稿 中尾村 鹿島明神社}}</ref>

Gyokurin-in, a temple of the {{ill|Shugendō|ja|修験道|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shugendō|qq=}} sect (Honzan-ha) founded in {{ill|790 AD|ja|790年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/790 AD|qq=}} (the 9th year of {{ill|Enryaku|ja|延暦|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Enryaku|qq=}}), was later forced into closure during the early {{ill|Meiji Period|ja|明治|1=Meiji era|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji Period|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji era|qq=}} due to the separation of Shinto and Buddhism.<ref name="神社">{{Cite book|lang=ja|title={{ill|Saitama Shrines: Shrines of Kita-Adachi, Kodama, and Minami Saitama|ja|埼玉の神社 北足立・児玉・南埼玉|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saitama Shrines: Shrines of Kita-Adachi, Kodama, and Minami Saitama|qq=}}|publisher={{ill|Saitama Prefecture Shrine Agency|ja|埼玉県神社庁|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saitama Prefecture Shrine Agency|qq=}}|date=1998|pages=142–143}}</ref>

Separated from Gyokurin-in, this shrine was originally known as "Kashima-sha" and was designated as a village shrine under the Modern Shrine Ranking System in {{ill|1873 AD|ja|1873年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1873 AD|qq=}} (Meiji 6). In {{ill|1908 AD|ja|1908年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1908 AD|qq=}} (Meiji 41), during a consolidation process, ten surrounding shrines were merged and the shrine was renamed "Nakao Shrine" based on its local place name. (This merger was only administrative; the individual shrines still exist.)<ref>{{R|"神社"}}</ref>

== Transportation ==
* A 26‑minute walk from {{ill|Higashi-Urawa Station|ja|東浦和駅|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Higashi-Urawa Station|qq=}}
* From the {{ill|Kokusai Kōgyō Bus|ja|国際興業バス|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kokusai Kōgyō Bus|qq=}} (Higashi-Urawa Station, Saitama East Office, line "Higashi-Urawa 03"), get off at "Nakao Daini Kōen" and walk 4 minutes.

