'''Nakao Shrine''' (中尾神社, なかおじんじゃ) is a Shinto shrine located in {{ill|Saitama Prefecture|en|Saitama Prefecture|qid=Q128186|lt=Saitama Prefecture|1=Saitama Prefecture}}, {{ill|Saitama (city)|en|Saitama (city)|qid=Q134635|lt=Saitama City|1=Saitama (city)}}, Midori Ward ({{ill|Midori-ku, Saitama|en|Midori-ku, Saitama|qid=Q1130733|lt=Midori Ward|1=Midori-ku, Saitama}}) of Japan.

== History ==
The founding date of the shrine is unknown. However, it is believed to have existed at least since the late {{ill|Edo period|en|Edo period|qid=Q184963|lt=Edo Period|1=Edo period}}, as it is mentioned in the geographical work 『{{ill|New Edition Musashi Fudoki-kō|ja|新編武蔵風土記稿|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/New Edition Musashi Fudoki-kō|1=Shinpen Musashi Fudoki-kō|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11503943}}』 as the subsidiary shrine "Kashima Myōjin-sha" of "Gyokurin-in."<ref name="">{{sfn|新編武蔵風土記稿 中尾村 鹿島明神社}}</ref>

Gyokurin-in, a temple of the {{ill|Shugendō|en|Shugendō|qid=Q1483875|lt=Shugendō|1=Shugendō}} sect (Honzan-ha) founded in {{ill|790|en|790|qid=Q31147|lt=790 AD|1=790}} (the 9th year of {{ill|Enryaku|en|Enryaku|qid=Q1373176|lt=Enryaku|1=Enryaku}}), was later forced into closure during the early {{ill|Meiji era|en|Meiji era|qid=Q3125096|lt=Meiji era|1=Meiji era}} due to the separation of Shinto and Buddhism.<ref name="神社">{{Cite book|lang=ja|title={{ill|Saitama Shrines: Shrines of Kita-Adachi, Kodama, and Minami Saitama|ja|埼玉の神社 北足立・児玉・南埼玉|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saitama Shrines: Shrines of Kita-Adachi, Kodama, and Minami Saitama|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}|publisher={{ill|Saitama Prefecture Shrine Agency|ja|埼玉県神社庁|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saitama Prefecture Shrine Agency|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 神社庁|1=Jinjachō|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11590703}}|date=1998|pages=142–143}}</ref>

Separated from Gyokurin-in, this shrine was originally known as "Kashima-sha" and was designated as a village shrine under the Modern Shrine Ranking System in {{ill|1873|en|1873|qid=Q7757|lt=1873 AD|1=1873}} (Meiji 6). In {{ill|1908|en|1908|qid=Q2056|lt=1908 AD|1=1908}} (Meiji 41), during a consolidation process, ten surrounding shrines were merged and the shrine was renamed "Nakao Shrine" based on its local place name. (This merger was only administrative; the individual shrines still exist.)<ref>{{R|"神社"}}</ref>

== Transportation ==
* A 26-minute walk from {{ill|Higashi-Urawa Station|en|Higashi-Urawa Station|qid=Q5753897|lt=Higashi-Urawa Station|1=Higashi-Urawa Station}}
* From the {{ill|Kokusai Kōgyō Bus|ja|国際興業バス|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kokusai Kōgyō Bus|1=Kokusai Kogyo Bus|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11422566}} (Higashi-Urawa Station, Saitama East Office, line "Higashi-Urawa 03"), get off at "Nakao Daini Kōen" and walk 4 minutes.

